snippet.textDisplay:
Othello Essay Draft 6

A text resonates with audiences over time, by transcending the conventions of its genre and exploring significant aspects of human experiences. William Shakespeare’s tragic play ‘Othello’ does this by exploring the thematic concerns of jealousy, appearance versus reality and an outsider status, which continue to resonate in society, and uses them to intricately construct a complex plot about betrayal and misunderstanding. Shakespeare employs dramatic and theatrical devices along with explicit literary techniques to develop flawed misguided characters who are exploited by those who manipulate them. 




Jealousy is a strong human experience that has a degrading effect on an individual and exposes the flaws in them. Shakespeare effectively emphasises the destructive power of jealousy, which corrupts the values of honour and trust. In Othello, the protagonist is a general who has a high social status known as the ‘valiant,’ moor and a respected member of the Venetian society. Shakespeare expresses this by writing in Iambic Pentameter but as the play progresses, the antagonist Iago schemes his motive for revenge by manipulating Othello with jealousy shown by the shift to prose. This is directly seen when Iago says, ‘O beware, my lord, of jealousy!, It is the green-eyed monster, which doth mock, The meat it feeds on’. Iago uses medieval imagery to capture the wrath of jealousy, also foreshadowing the ending of the play by  metaphorically saying it ‘doth mock, The meat it feeds on’, suggesting that if Othello gives into jealousy, it will ironically destroy him. In the temptation scene Iago exploits the truth of the ‘eye’ by manipulating appearance versus reality when he tells Othello,‘Look to your wife; observe her well with Cassio; Wear your eyes thus: not jealous nor secure’. By using truncated sentences, possessive nouns and paradoxically falsifying the truth, Iago manipulates Othello, evoking an emotion of betrayal in him.  Iago further corrupts Othello by manipulating the actions of the handkerchief which symbolises love and trust. In Act 4 when Othello says  "Lie with her? Lie on her?... Handkerchief! - Oh, devil!”, the use of prose, repetition of ‘lie’ and broken sentence structure clearly show us the crippling effect of jealousy in causing Othello’s misunderstanding of the situation. Shakespeare exposes Othello’s flaw of manipulation exploiting his sense of betrayal and misunderstanding leading to the ultimate downfall of him.

 




Appearance versus reality is a common human experience that is an illusion to the truth and creates misunderstanding. Shakespeare explores appearance versus reality by developing Iago, a character whose motive for revenge is hidden under a facade of loyalty and ‘honesty’. Iago confirms this in Act 1 Scene 1 in his dramatic monologue when he says ‘I am not what I am’. The binary contradiction clearly establishes Iago’s duplicity and demonic nature, showing him as the master of appearance versus reality as his external appearance merely conceals his inner self. To support this Iago’s soliloquy,’I’ll put the Moor in jealousy so strong that judgement cannot cure’ further reveals his evil nature which he conceals through deceit. As the play develops and Othello is introduced, Iago constantly feeds misleading information to him by perverting the understanding of his observations. By planting seeds of doubt in Othello's mind, Iago launches him into a state of denial which Shakespeare expresses by including dreams and trances about betrayal. However Othello is warned about the negative repercussions of appearance versus reality in Act 1 Scene 3 with Brabantio’s soliloquy ‘Look to her, if thou hast eyes to see, she has deceived her father and may thee’. Brabantio foreshadows Othello’s cause for misunderstanding and sense of betrayal by implying for him to use his ‘eyes to see’. Ironically later when Othello judges Desdemona he is so corrupted by Iago's lies that he is unable to ‘see’ the truth in her. Towards the end of the play corruption due to Iago's manipulation of appearance versus reality is seen in Othello's soliloquy, ‘He had my handkerchief!... Handkerchief!... Handkerchief!’. The repetition embodies his frenzied state of fury and the ‘handkerchief’ now symbolises betrayal. By using literary devices Shakespeare makes Iago the master of appearance versus reality by manipulating Othello to change from being a man who judges by what he ‘sees’, to judging by what he hears.

In the play Othello, Shakespeare highlights the tragic consequences of a change in perception which destablises Othello and exposes him as an outsider. Ironically, it is Iago who manipulates Othello’s status and authority by being his only source of information. Iago’s rage and revulsion, shown by plosive language in his blunt soliloquy ‘I hate the Moor’, is contrasted to Othello’s self-assurance shown through the repeated metonym of ‘valiant’. In Acts I and 2, Othello is shown as a man in control and at the pinnacle of his career through the imperative, “Good Signior, you shall more command with years than with your weapons.” He speaks calmly and assertively to a racist Brabantio who accuses him of committing ‘witchcraft’. Shakespeare constructs a fluent, assertive quality to Othello’s speech through Iambic Pentameter.  Iago is his antithesis by being duplicit and after manipulating Othello, he exposes his insecurities about being an outsider. Iago does this by articulating racial slurs and negative animal imagery such as ‘Old black ram’ and ‘barbary horse’ to emphasise Othello's outsider appearance and contrast his animal like quality to the pure Venetian ‘white ewes’. Furthermore, Iago effectively exploits Othello's flaw of naivety using his gullibility to his advantage to destabilise him. Following tragic shakespearean convention, after realising his wrongful murder, in Othellos epiphanic soliloquy, “Speak of me as I am; nothing extenuates” he accepts responsibility through his inclusive language of ‘me’ and ‘I’ and attempts to regain his ‘valiant’ identity. After discovering his fatal flaws, he compares himself in a simile as a ‘base Judean who threw a pearl away", accepting the Elizabethan notion that Africans are ‘base’ or uncivilised and he couldn't conform to the white ‘pearl’ Venetian society. By using literary devices and theatrical conventions, Shakespeare exploits the honour of Othello and destabilizes him by exposing his flaws.






Shakespeare's play ‘Othello’ has resonated over time by exploring the themes of jealousy, appearance versus reality and racial prejudice, and using them to intricately construct a complex plot about betrayal and misunderstanding. Shakespeare does this by employing dramatic and theatrical devices as well as stunning literary techniques to develop misguided characters that fall to the flaws of their human experiences.

Ironically, it is Iago who manipulates Othello’s status and authority by being his only source of information. Iago’s rage and revulsion, shown by plosive language in his blunt soliloquy ‘I hate the Moor’, is contrasted to Othello’s self-assurance shown through the repeated metonym of ‘valiant’. In Acts I and 2, Othello is shown as a man in control and at the pinnacle of his career through the imperative, “Good Signior, you shall more command with years than with your weapons.” He speaks calmly and assertively to a racist Brabantio who accuses him of committing ‘witchcraft’. Shakespeare constructs a fluent, assertive quality to Othello’s speech through Iambic Pentameter.  Iago is his antithesis by being duplicit and after manipulating Othello, he exposes his insecurities about being an outsider. Iago does this by articulating racial slurs and negative animal imagery such as ‘Old black ram’ and ‘barbary horse’ to emphasise Othello's outsider appearance and contrast his animal like quality to the pure Venetian ‘white ewes’. Furthermore, Iago effectively exploits Othello's flaw of naivety using his gullibility to his advantage to destabilise him. Following tragic shakespearean convention, after realising his wrongful murder, in Othellos epiphanic soliloquy, “Speak of me as I am; nothing extenuates” he accepts responsibility through his inclusive language of ‘me’ and ‘I’ and attempts to regain his ‘valiant’ identity. After discovering his fatal flaws, he compares himself in a simile as a ‘base Judean who threw a pearl away", accepting the Elizabethan notion that Africans are ‘base’ or uncivilised and he couldn't conform to the white ‘pearl’ Venetian society. By using literary devices and theatrical conventions, Shakespeare exploits the honour of Othello and destabilizes him by exposing his flaws.






Shakespeare's play ‘Othello’ has resonated over time by exploring the themes of jealousy, appearance versus reality and racial prejudice, and using them to intricately construct a complex plot about betrayal and misunderstanding. Shakespeare does this by employing dramatic and theatrical devices as well as stunning literary techniques to develop misguided characters that fall to the flaws of their human experiences.
